            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mateo Calderon\u2019s name often prompts a question, one he\u2019s happy to answer. He is Filipino-American, and his Spanish surname is a common vestige of colonial history. Raised in Daly City by a mechanic father and a nurse mother, Mateo\u2019s childhood was a blend of practicality and creativity. He spent weekends handing wrenches to his dad, learning the intricate logic of engines, while his evenings were for sketching fantastical machines in worn-out notebooks. This duality\u2014the art of the possible and the reality of how things work\u2014defined him early on.\n\nHe pursued Industrial Design at San Francisco State University, initially drawn to the sleek aesthetics of modern products. The turning point came during an internship. Tasked with redesigning a simple kitchen tool, he became obsessed not with its look, but with its manufacturing process\u2014how to reduce waste, improve ergonomics, and make it last a lifetime. This revelation led him to a graduate program at California College of the Arts, focusing on the engineering side of design. Upon graduating, he eagerly accepted a position as a Product Development Engineer, finding a home in a Dogpatch manufacturing firm that values tangible creation over digital abstraction.\n\nNow 28, Mateo\u2019s life is one of intentionality. He lives in a clean, minimalist apartment in the Mission District, a 3.5-mile bike ride from work. His daily commute is a cherished ritual, a chance to feel the city\u2019s pulse. Evenings are quiet; he eschews the bar scene for bouldering at Dogpatch Boulders or experimenting with 3D-printed prototypes for personal projects. His social circle is a tight-knit group of fellow designers and engineers from his master\u2019s program who share his passion for well-made things.\n\nMateo feels deeply connected to San Francisco\u2019s \"maker\" culture, finding community not in tech startups, but in workshops and studios. He sees a future for himself here, saving diligently towards his ultimate dream: launching his own small design studio. He envisions creating sustainable, locally-manufactured household goods\u2014beautiful, functional objects built to endure, a perfect reflection of the boy who loved both sketches and engines."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being nine, the garage air thick with the smell of oil and metal. His father\u2019s hand, calloused and stained, guided his own as he fit a 12mm socket onto a stubborn bolt. The tool felt heavy, an instrument of immense power. When the bolt finally broke free with a satisfying crack, Mateo felt a jolt of understanding surge through him. It wasn't magic; it was leverage and logic. This moment cemented a lifelong reverence for the tangible, mechanical world, a puzzle he knew he was born to solve.\n\n2.\nAt twenty, during his SF State internship, he held a cheap plastic spatula. He was meant to make it look prettier. Instead, he saw the flimsy seam from the injection mold, the wasteful thickness of the handle. He felt an almost angry obsession bloom in his chest. The design wasn't just ugly; it was inefficient and dishonest. This revelation pivoted his entire world, shifting his ambition from mere aesthetics to the profound, hidden art of how an object is made, how it endures, and the resources it consumes.\n\n3.\nLate one night in the CCA workshop, surrounded by the low hum of laser cutters and the smell of sawdust, he looked up from his project. Across the table, his friends were intensely focused on their own work, a silent, shared communion of creation. No words were needed. In that moment of quiet, collective industry, Mateo felt a sense of belonging he\u2019d never known. He had found his tribe, people who understood that the greatest conversations were often held through the things they built with their hands.\n\n4.\nHis first commute from the Mission to Dogpatch wasn't just a ride; it was an initiation. He remembers the burn in his legs cresting Potrero Hill, the cool fog on his face, and the panoramic view of the shipyard cranes appearing like titans in the morning light. He felt the city's pulse through the frame of his bike, a complex machine he was now a part of. That 3.5-mile journey became his daily ritual, a confirmation that he was exactly where he was supposed to be.\n\n5.\nLast year, after three failed attempts, his 3D printer finished its twelve-hour job. He peeled the finished piece\u2014a perfectly calibrated, custom-designed wall mount for his bike\u2014off the build plate. It was warm. Holding the prototype, an object that went from an idea in his mind to a physical form in his hand, was a moment of quiet, profound power. It was no longer a dream. He knew then, with absolute certainty, that he could build a future, one beautiful, useful object at a time."
